      'result': """P0f is a passive operating system (OS) fingerprinting tool designed to analyze TCP/IP packet headers, particularly SYN packets, to identify the operating system and other characteristics of a remote host without sending any active probes. This means p0f observes existing network traffic rather than actively scanning for open ports. Therefore, using "p0f" to "scan" a Nintendo 3DS for an open port 25565 related to Minecraft is a misunderstanding of how p0f operates, as it does not actively probe targets.

Port 25565 is the default port used by Minecraft: Java Edition servers for incoming connections. Setting up a Minecraft Java Edition server typically requires configuring port forwarding on a router to allow external players to connect to this port.

However, the "Minecraft: New Nintendo 3DS Edition" is a distinct version of the game designed for the handheld console. This edition functions as a self-contained game on the device and is not known to host servers that would utilize port 25565 for external connections in the same manner as a PC-based Minecraft: Java Edition server. Consequently, attempting to scan a Nintendo 3DS for an open port 25565 for Minecraft would likely not yield relevant results, as the console's version of the game does not operate with this networking model."""
    }
  )
